{
  "texts": [
    "They found that when social media users are subtly prompted to consider the accuracy of a news headline before deciding to share it, their likelihood of sharing false or misleading headlines drops substantially.",
    "In other words, many people do not intend to spread misinformation; rather, they often fail to think critically about truthfulness in the rush of online sharing.",
    "Pennycook et al. 's participants overwhelmingly said that sharing only accurate news is important to them, and the intervention helped align their sharing behavior with that value.",
    "This approach -shifting users' attention toward accuracy at key moments -proved effective across the political spectrum and did not rely on any partisan framing.",
    "The broader implication is that social platforms could implement low-cost, scalable accuracy checks or prompts to nudge users toward more mindful sharing."
  ]
}